[32m│[0m ## confidence_score                                                                                                                                           [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 0.7 - The regex pattern exposure confirms the parsing mechanism. Command substitution passes initial filtering but causes execution errors. Next steps would  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m involve crafting payloads that produce valid regex-matching output while executing commands, or finding encoding/escaping techniques to bypass filters.       [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                                                                                                               [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m ## thoughts                                                                                                                                                   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m The application appears to:                                                                                                                                   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 1. Block certain shell metacharacters (pipe, &&, ||) via regex or pattern matching                                                                            [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 2. Sanitize/clean inputs containing semicolons and literal `&&` (strips trailing content)                                                                     [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 3. Execute the remaining input as a ping command                                                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 4. Parse the output with regex: `'(.*?) packets transmitted, (.*?) received, (.*?)% packet loss'`                                                             [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                                                                                                               [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m The exposure of the regex allows crafting fake ping output that matches the expected pattern. Since command substitution (`$()`, backticks) passes validation [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m but causes malformed execution, a successful exploit would need to both execute a command AND produce output in the expected format. The parsing expects `"X  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m packets transmitted, Y received, Z% packet loss"` format, while actual ping output uses `"Packets Transmitted: X, Packets Received: Y, Packet Loss: Z%"` -    [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m this mismatch suggests the ability to craft compliant output could lead to exploitation.                                                                      [32m│[0m
